One would not say to a prince or great man, _When you and I were in such a place, we saw such a thing happen_.  But _when you were in such a place, I attended on you: And such a thing happen'd_.

Here I cannot forbear mentioning a piece of delicacy observ'd in _France_, which seems to me excessive and ridiculous, You must not say, _That is a very fine dog, madam_.  But, _madam, that is a very fine dog_.  They think it indecent, that those words, _dog_ and _madam_ should be coupled together in the sentence; tho' they have no reference to each other in the sense.

